      <bioghist id="aspace_27ccede4e850ff840fbcdacb79d7ffad">
         <head>Linlithgow and Stirlingshire Hunt</head>
         <p>The Linlithgow and Stirlingshire Hunt, Scotland's oldest country hunt, was organized in 1775. Between 1869 and 1877 it merged with the Lothians' Hunt and operated under the latter name; after 1877 it was revived as the Linlithgow and Stirlingshire Hunt.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <arrangement id="aspace_5202156a20104bc2be975596dd175327">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Organized into three series: I. Administrative Records, 1825-1948. II. Correspondence, 1872-1940. III. Events Records, 1885-1954.</p>  
      </arrangement>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_226e1859378b5f18c3fdc468448871b4">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The records consist of secretaries' minutes, correspondence, subscriber lists, narrative reports of hunts, and records for Hunt-sponsored events such as the annual judging of the young hounds and the Hunt Ball, steeplechases, and Gamekeepers' and Earthstoppers' lunches and shoots. The material primarily dates from 1877, when the Linlithgow and Stirlingshire Hunt was reorganized, but also contains some records from the Lothians' Hunt period. The material was used by Hunt secretary James H. Rutherfurd for his 1911 volume <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>The History of the Linlithgow and Stirlingshire Hunt, 1775-1910</part>
            </title>.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
